{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445082868,"nonce":"0oYIvH6E1Q4obhEodsEhtcwZfQo=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkxMTEzMg==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148911132"},"message":"\u003e \u003e Oh, yes this in discussed a lot. We can define a data type for count-data, but we can not even make this unique for htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts ;)\n\u003e \n\u003e Why not? It's true we'd need to do this for htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts, but if we decide on a common datatype with common metadata, then we'd only need to map Identifiers and counts in the datatype. I'm a bit vague here, admittedly, but it would be nice if galaxy tools could transparently handle the native dataformats produced by htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts, since the kind of information they provide is the same.\n\nDifferent number of columns, different headers/comment lines. Thinking about it I don't know what is similar between them ;)\nfeatureCount is even worse, as it does not mark the comment line with `#` or similar symbols. \nSo we need to recognise `Geneid 1:`, which is not really unique. Also please consider what happens if this identifier is changing between featureCounts versions, for example to `Gene-ID 1:`. You need to have a new data type to detect this. Versioned datatypes are currently not supported.","files":null}]}